NUMBERED ALGORITHMIC FORM (Plain Text · Finite · Executable)

	1	Take a term T.
	2	Can a literate human understand T by reading plain text?
	3	If no → reject T.
	4	Can T be counted, bounded, or listed?
	5	If no → reject T.
	6	Does T rely on authority, secrecy, or credentials?
	7	If yes → reject T.
	8	Is there a clear condition where T would be false?
	9	If no → reject T.
	10	Can responsibility for outcomes be named?
	11	If no → reject T.
	12	Otherwise → accept T.


or an oral algorithm (a child can remember)

Say this:
“If a word hides more than it shows, throw it out. If you can’t test it yourself, throw it out. If it needs an authority to be true, throw it out. If it can’t fail, it’s lying. If no one is responsible, it’s poison. What remains — keep.”


    


        



  